<subSubSection id="E1372B51FA345193EC8B8D31B52EA7C8" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8EBEAA1AE816B78242473353217C605F" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3733B60E120F68B64C12641F4D398CB4" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">
This species is widely distributed in Africa. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="2EF21F6A3A1C41519B90095791327D8C" author="Prost, A" journalOrPublisher="Denisia" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" refId="B95" refString="Prost, A, 2013. The Genus Ascalaphus (Fabricius, 1775) (Neuroptera, Ascalaphidae) in Africa Acoreana, Suplemento 9: 57-72." title="The Genus Ascalaphus (Fabricius, 1775) (Neuroptera, Ascalaphidae) in Africa Acoreana, Suplemento 9: 57 - 72." year="2013">Prost (2013)</bibRefCitation>
it is found in the Republic of South Africa, West Africa (Chad, Niger, Burkina Faso, Mali, Senegal, Ghana and Liberia) and on the northern coast of Africa. 
<bibRefCitation id="14E07837ED09AD8F14905E54A8F8B8F6" author="Pantaleoni, RA" journalOrPublisher="Biodiversity Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" pagination="179 - 182" refId="B91" refString="Pantaleoni, RA, Badano, D, Aspoeck, U, Aspoeck, H, 2013. Ascalaphus festivus (Rambur, 1842) in Sardinia, a new genus of Ascalaphidae for Europe (Neuroptera). Biodiversity Journal 4: 179 - 182" title="Ascalaphus festivus (Rambur, 1842) in Sardinia, a new genus of Ascalaphidae for Europe (Neuroptera)." volume="4" year="2013">Pantaleoni et al. (2013)</bibRefCitation>
published surprising records from southern Sardinia (Italy). 
<bibRefCitation id="64F5B1D8B20AAA986DD5D5C6AC6B5A81" author="Aspoeck, H" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Fifth International Symposium on Neuropterology (2 - 6 May 1994, Cairo, Egypt). Privately printed, Toulouse, France" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" refId="B8" refString="Aspoeck, H, Hoelzel, H, Aspoeck, U, 2001. Kommentierter Katalog der Neuropterida (Insecta: Raphidioptera, Megaloptera, Neuroptera) der Westpalaearktis.2: 1-606." title="Kommentierter Katalog der Neuropterida (Insecta: Raphidioptera, Megaloptera, Neuroptera) der Westpalaearktis. 2: 1 - 606." year="2001">
<normalizedToken id="5B92BCA1C344A759EC54B4D6D9D6CC1F" originalValue="Aspöck">Aspoeck</normalizedToken>
et al. (2001)
</bibRefCitation>
documented the species on the border region of Southwest Palaearctic (Israel, Saudi Arabia, Oman, Yemen, the United Arab Emirates, Tunisia and the Cape Verde Islands). Its occurrence in Egypt (
<normalizedToken id="2F1DA3DC753474CF4E7224A5911920C3" originalValue="Navás">Navas</normalizedToken>
1913) was confirmed by 
<bibRefCitation id="7C2AFB8435196CBE1D73CDBD5C65DFA9" author="Prost, A" journalOrPublisher="Denisia" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" refId="B95" refString="Prost, A, 2013. The Genus Ascalaphus (Fabricius, 1775) (Neuroptera, Ascalaphidae) in Africa Acoreana, Suplemento 9: 57-72." title="The Genus Ascalaphus (Fabricius, 1775) (Neuroptera, Ascalaphidae) in Africa Acoreana, Suplemento 9: 57 - 72." year="2013">Prost (2013)</bibRefCitation>
. It is a new record for the fauna of Jordan. Further specimens can be found in the collection of SCMK (
<normalizedToken id="C08D3DD25D1E4DAC8B82E1D720A2BCAA" originalValue="Kaposvár">Kaposvar</normalizedToken>
) from Namibia, Zambia, Tanzania, Kenya and Ethiopia. A closely related taxon from Madagascar is treated by 
<bibRefCitation id="4192D17A347D3C400851ECE7676DA1A9" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1163/187631280794710006" author="Tjeder, B" journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Scandinavica" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" pagination="401 - 412" refId="B105" refString="Tjeder, B, 1980. Ascalaphidae (Neuroptera) from Senegal and the Gambia. Entomologica Scandinavica 11: 401 - 412, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1163/187631280794710006" title="Ascalaphidae (Neuroptera) from Senegal and the Gambia." url="https://doi.org/10.1163/187631280794710006" volume="11" year="1980">Tjeder (1980)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="89C794FADD295BF60175B03D22D56449" author="Prost, A" journalOrPublisher="Denisia" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" refId="B95" refString="Prost, A, 2013. The Genus Ascalaphus (Fabricius, 1775) (Neuroptera, Ascalaphidae) in Africa Acoreana, Suplemento 9: 57-72." title="The Genus Ascalaphus (Fabricius, 1775) (Neuroptera, Ascalaphidae) in Africa Acoreana, Suplemento 9: 57 - 72." year="2013">Prost (2013)</bibRefCitation>
as a separate species under the name 
<taxonomicName id="A9456AEF2420691F90F203ADCAF8DEF0" baseAuthorityName="McLachlan" baseAuthorityYear="1871" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Ascalaphus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ascalaphus africanus" order="Neuroptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="africanus">
<emphasis id="12FA35604CDA178A4321A493B3C40F5B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Ascalaphus africanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(McLachlan, 1871), which is also mentioned from Mozambique (
<bibRefCitation id="185CF404479AEFDE258BB0C2A0C9D326" author="Prost, A" journalOrPublisher="Denisia" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" refId="B95" refString="Prost, A, 2013. The Genus Ascalaphus (Fabricius, 1775) (Neuroptera, Ascalaphidae) in Africa Acoreana, Suplemento 9: 57-72." title="The Genus Ascalaphus (Fabricius, 1775) (Neuroptera, Ascalaphidae) in Africa Acoreana, Suplemento 9: 57 - 72." year="2013">Prost 2013</bibRefCitation>
). In the future, it would be worthwhile to confirm morphologically separated species by genetic testing.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="748BC067511631FDA428AE377BB7B86F" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" type="comments">
<paragraph id="C88D1C64BB5C0D328CA9B3B929962515" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D5DDBD419154C143BA785C1911D37AF9" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">
This species was found in a marsh near a hot spring and local water seeps. The vegetation was characterized by scattered date palms (
<taxonomicName id="2A122535CBB0A51E24931A1CFC254C72" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Phoenix" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Phoenix dactylifera" order="Arecales" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dactylifera">
<emphasis id="064D70362CCCF2997B7BC181227F9ED8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Phoenix dactylifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and covered with 
<taxonomicName id="DADBFE9DFCCEB208B20DE2874C8555EA" class="Liliopsida" family="Juncaceae" genus="Juncus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Juncus" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="55383E1A22909A1F03A4B9D66673BA25" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Juncus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="0F5C0319E7C7A3164F39BF4D7E858E81" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Saccharum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Saccharum" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6ABCB2D43E99A009C2E6CCA33E51FEF8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Saccharum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Figs 
<figureCitation id="25CF9E504233CFB31E772143BE62CB02" captionStart="Figures 1–8" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 8. 1. Habitus of Ascalaphus festivus female. 2. Habitus of A. festivus male. 3. Habitat of A. festivus near the Dead Sea, August 2009. 4. Habitat of A. festivus near the Dead Sea, December 2015. 5. Habitus of Stylascalaphus krueperi female. 6. Habitus of S. krueperi male. 7. Habitat of S. krueperi, Wadi Kufrinja Valley, August 2009. 8. Habitat of S. krueperi, Wadi Afra Valley, August 2009. Pictures: all C. Monnerat." figureDoi="10.3897/alpento.4.50696.figures1-8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427119" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="786885E336AE1741609E1086F1C6FC03" captionStart="Figures 1–8" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 8. 1. Habitus of Ascalaphus festivus female. 2. Habitus of A. festivus male. 3. Habitat of A. festivus near the Dead Sea, August 2009. 4. Habitat of A. festivus near the Dead Sea, December 2015. 5. Habitus of Stylascalaphus krueperi female. 6. Habitus of S. krueperi male. 7. Habitat of S. krueperi, Wadi Kufrinja Valley, August 2009. 8. Habitat of S. krueperi, Wadi Afra Valley, August 2009. Pictures: all C. Monnerat." figureDoi="10.3897/alpento.4.50696.figures1-8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427119" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">4</figureCitation>
). Males and females were found during the day sitting on stems and collected with insect nets. The locality to the north of Wadi Mujib near the Dead Sea is the lowest observation point on earth for this species at 316 m b.s.l. and is located in the Sudanian bioclimatic region characterized by tropical influences. The species was found in Oman and Saudi Arabia near wadis, in their flood plains, or in oases (C. Monnerat, personal observation). In Sardinia, 
<taxonomicName id="16D5E03CB3796FDD8147206A67436AD2" genus="A." lsidName="A. festivus" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" rank="species" species="festivus">
<emphasis id="D064A674AE43AC49E127A1AF73B32325" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">A. festivus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found in coastal salt marshes (
<bibRefCitation id="9A0732D051EB6F8A725203B285E3C20A" author="Pantaleoni, RA" journalOrPublisher="Biodiversity Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" pagination="179 - 182" refId="B91" refString="Pantaleoni, RA, Badano, D, Aspoeck, U, Aspoeck, H, 2013. Ascalaphus festivus (Rambur, 1842) in Sardinia, a new genus of Ascalaphidae for Europe (Neuroptera). Biodiversity Journal 4: 179 - 182" title="Ascalaphus festivus (Rambur, 1842) in Sardinia, a new genus of Ascalaphidae for Europe (Neuroptera)." volume="4" year="2013">Pantaleoni et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
